# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: terra-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] In computer science, **ahead-of-time compilation** (**AOT compilation**) is the act of compiling an (often) higher-level programming language into an (often) lower-level language before execution of a program, usually at build-time, to reduce the amount of work needed to be performed at run time.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] When being used in this context, it is often seen as an opposite of just-in-time (JIT) compiling.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Speaking more generally, the target languages of an AOT compilation are not necessarily specific to native machine code but are defined rather arbitrarily.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some academic papers use this word to mean the act of compiling the Java bytecode to C or the timing when optimization pipeline are performed.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] An academic project uses this word to mean the act of pre-compiling JavaScript to a machine-dependent optimized IR for V8 (JavaScript engine) and to a machine independent bytecode for JavaScriptCore.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some industrial language implementations (e.g.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Clojure and Hermes JavaScript engine) use this word to mean the act of pre-compiling the source language to VM specific bytecode.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Angular (web framework) uses this word to mean converting its HTML template and TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] In fact, since all static compilation is technically performed ahead of time, this particular wording is often used to emphasize examples where there are significant performance advantages over the act of such pre-compiling.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] The act of compiling Java to Java bytecode is hence rarely referred to as AOT since it is usually a requirement, not an optimization.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some programming languages with a managed code runtime that can be compiled to an intermediate representation use just-in-time (JIT) compiling.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] This briefly compiles intermediate code into machine code for a native run while the intermediate code is executing which may slow an application's performance.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Ahead-of-time compiling eliminates the need for this step by occurring before execution rather than during execution.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Ahead-of-time compiling for dynamically typed languages to native machine code or other static VM bytecode is possible in a limited number of cases only.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] For example, the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) AOT compiler for the language Erlang can do this because of advanced static type reconstruction techniques and type speculations.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] In most situations with fully AOT compiled programs and libraries, it is possible to remove part of a runtime environment, thus saving disk space, memory, battery life, and startup times (no JIT warmup phase), etc.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Because of this, it can be useful in embedded or mobile devices.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] AOT compilers can perform complex and advanced code optimizations which in most cases of JITing will be considered much too costly.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] In contrast, AOT usually cannot perform some optimizations possible in JIT like runtime profile-guided optimization (PGO), pseudo-constant propagation, or indirect-virtual function inlining.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] AOT must compile to a target architecture while a JIT can compile the code to make the best use of the actual CPU it is running on, even years after the software has been released.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Further, JIT compilers can speculatively optimize hot code by making assumptions on the code.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] The generated code can be deoptimized if a speculative assumption later proves wrong.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Such operation slows the performance of the running software until code is optimized again by adaptive optimization.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] An AOT compiler cannot make such assumptions and needs to infer as much information as possible at compile time.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] It needs to resort to less specialized code because it cannot know what types will go through a method.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] Such problems can be alleviated by profile-guided optimizations.
[src:terra-language/ahead-of-time-compilation] But even in this case, the generated code cannot be adapted dynamically to the changing runtime profile as a JIT compiler would do.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:terra-language/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM is written in C++ and is designed for compile-time, link-time, and runtime optimization.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The LLVM project started in 2000 at the University of Illinois Urbana–Champaign, under the direction of Vikram Adve and Chris Lattner.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM was originally developed as a research infrastructure to investigate dynamic compilation techniques for static and dynamic programming languages.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM was released under the University of Illinois/NCSA Open Source License, a permissive free software licence.
[src:terra-language/llvm] In 2005, Apple Inc. hired Lattner and formed a team to work on the LLVM system for various uses within Apple's development systems.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM has been an integral part of Apple's Xcode development tools for macOS and iOS since Xcode 4 in 2011.
[src:terra-language/llvm] In 2006, Lattner started working on a new project named Clang.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The combination of the Clang frontend and LLVM backend is named Clang/LLVM or simply Clang.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The name *LLVM* was originally an initialism for *Low Level Virtual Machine*.
[src:terra-language/llvm] However, the LLVM project evolved into an umbrella project that has little relationship to what most current developers think of as a virtual machine.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This made the initialism "confusing" and "inappropriate", and since 2011 LLVM is "officially no longer an acronym", but a brand that applies to the LLVM umbrella project.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The project encompasses the LLVM intermediate representation (IR), the LLVM debugger, the LLVM implementation of the C++ Standard Library (with full support of C++11 and C++14), etc.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM is administered by the LLVM Foundation.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Compiler engineer Tanya Lattner became its president in 2014 and was still president and Executive Director as of November 2025.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The project was originally available under the UIUC license.
[src:terra-language/llvm] After v9.0.0 released in 2019, LLVM relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:terra-language/llvm] As of November 2022 about 400 contributions had not been relicensed.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM can provide the middle layers of a complete compiler system, taking intermediate representation (IR) code from a compiler and emitting an optimized IR.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This new IR can then be converted and linked into machine-dependent assembly language code for a target platform.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM can accept the IR from the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain, allowing it to be used with a wide array of extant compiler front-ends written for that project.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM can also be built with gcc after version 7.5.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM can also generate relocatable machine code at compile-time or link-time or even binary machine code at runtime.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM supports a language-independent instruction set and type system.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Each instruction is in static single assignment form (SSA), meaning that each variable (called a typed register) is assigned once and then frozen.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This helps simplify the analysis of dependencies among variables.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM allows code to be compiled statically, as it is under the traditional GCC system, or left for late-compiling from the IR to machine code via just-in-time compilation (JIT), similar to Java.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The type system consists of basic types such as integer or floating-point numbers and five derived types: pointers, arrays, vectors, structures, and functions.
[src:terra-language/llvm] A type construct in a concrete language can be represented by combining these basic types in LLVM.
[src:terra-language/llvm] For example, a class in C++ can be represented by a mix of structures, functions and arrays of function pointers.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The LLVM JIT compiler can optimize unneeded static branches out of a program at runtime, and thus is useful for partial evaluation in cases where a program has many options, most of which can easily be determined unneeded in a specific environment.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This feature is used in the OpenGL pipeline of Mac OS X Leopard (v10.5) to provide support for missing hardware features.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Graphics code within the OpenGL stack can be left in intermediate representation and then compiled when run on the target machine.
[src:terra-language/llvm] On systems with high-end graphics processing units (GPUs), the resulting code remains quite thin, passing the instructions on to the GPU with minimal changes.
[src:terra-language/llvm] On systems with low-end GPUs, LLVM will compile optional procedures that run on the local central processing unit (CPU) that emulate instructions that the GPU cannot run internally.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM improved performance on low-end machines using Intel GMA chipsets.
[src:terra-language/llvm] A similar system was developed under the Gallium3D LLVMpipe, and incorporated into the GNOME shell to allow it to run without a proper 3D hardware driver loaded.
[src:terra-language/llvm] In 2011, programs compiled by GCC outperformed those from LLVM by 10%, on average.
[src:terra-language/llvm] In 2013, phoronix reported that LLVM had caught up with GCC, compiling binaries of approximately equal performance.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM has become an umbrella project containing multiple components.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM was originally written to be a replacement for the extant code generator in the GCC stack, and many of the GCC frontends were modified to work with it, resulting in the now-defunct LLVM-GCC suite.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The modifications generally involved a GIMPLE-to-LLVM IR step so that LLVM optimizers and codegen could be used instead of GCC's GIMPLE system.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Apple was a significant user of LLVM-GCC through Xcode 4.x (2013).
[src:terra-language/llvm] This use of the GCC frontend was considered a temporary measure; it became mostly obsolete with Apple's development of Clang, a newer compiler frontend, with a more modern, modular codebase and greater compilation speed, supporting C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Support for LLVM-GCC was dropped in Xcode 5.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Primarily supported by Apple, Clang was aimed at replacing the C/Objective-C compiler in the GCC system with a system that is more easily integrated with integrated development environments (IDEs) and has wider support for multithreading.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Support for OpenMP directives has been included in Clang since release 3.8.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Widespread interest in LLVM has led to several efforts to develop new frontends for many other languages, including Ada, D, Delphi, Fortran, Haskell, Julia, Rust, Swift, and others.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The Utrecht Haskell compiler can generate code for LLVM.
[src:terra-language/llvm] While the generator was in early stages of development, in many cases it was more efficient than the C code generator.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) backend uses LLVM and achieves a 30% speed-up of compiled code relative to native code compiling via GHC or C code generation followed by compiling, missing only one of the many optimizing techniques implemented by the GHC.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Many other components are in various stages of development, including, but not limited to, a Java bytecode frontend, a Common Intermediate Language (CIL) frontend, the MacRuby implementation of Ruby 1.9, various frontends for Standard ML, and a new graph coloring register allocator.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The core of LLVM is the intermediate representation (IR), a low-level programming language similar to assembly.
[src:terra-language/llvm] IR is a strongly typed reduced instruction set computer (RISC) instruction set which abstracts away most details of the target.
[src:terra-language/llvm] For example, the calling convention is abstracted through `call` and `ret` instructions with explicit arguments.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Also, instead of a fixed set of registers, IR uses an infinite set of temporaries of the form %0, %1, etc.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM supports three equivalent forms of IR: a human-readable assembly format, an in-memory format suitable for frontends, and a dense bitcode format for serializing.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The many different conventions used and features provided by different targets mean that LLVM cannot truly produce a target-independent IR and retarget it without breaking some established rules.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Examples of target dependence beyond what is explicitly mentioned in the documentation can be found in a 2011 proposal for "wordcode", a fully target-independent variant of LLVM IR intended for online distribution.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The LLVM project also introduces another type of intermediate representation named MLIR which helps build reusable and extensible compiler infrastructure by employing a plugin architecture named Dialect.
[src:terra-language/llvm] It enables the use of higher-level information on the program structure in the process of optimization including polyhedral compilation.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Some features are not available on some platforms.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Most features are present for IA-32, x86-64, z/Architecture, ARM, and PowerPC.
[src:terra-language/llvm] In the past, LLVM also supported other backends, fully or partially, including C backend, Cell SPU, mblaze (MicroBlaze), AMD R600, DEC/Compaq Alpha (Alpha AXP) and Nios2, but that hardware is mostly obsolete, and LLVM developers decided the support and maintenance costs were no longer justified.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM also supports WebAssembly as a target, enabling compiled programs to execute in WebAssembly-enabled environments such as Google Chrome / Chromium, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari or WAVM.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM-compliant WebAssembly compilers typically support mostly unmodified source code written in C, C++, D, Rust, Nim, Kotlin and several other languages.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The LLVM machine code (MC) subproject is LLVM's framework for translating machine instructions between textual forms and machine code.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Formerly, LLVM relied on the system assembler, or one provided by a toolchain, to translate assembly into machine code.
[src:terra-language/llvm] LLVM MC's integrated assembler supports most LLVM targets, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, and ARM64.
[src:terra-language/llvm] For some targets, including the various MIPS instruction sets, integrated assembly support is usable but still in the beta stage.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The lld subproject is an attempt to develop a built-in, platform-independent linker for LLVM. lld aims to remove dependence on a third-party linker.
[src:terra-language/llvm] As of May 2017, lld supports ELF, PE/COFF, Mach-O, and WebAssembly in descending order of completeness. lld is faster than both flavors of GNU ld.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Unlike the GNU linkers, lld has built-in support for link-time optimization (LTO).
[src:terra-language/llvm] This allows for faster code generation as it bypasses the use of a linker plugin, but on the other hand prohibits interoperability with other flavors of LTO.
[src:terra-language/llvm] The LLVM project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library named libc++, dual-licensed under the MIT License and the UIUC license.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Since v9.0.0, it was relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This implements a suite of cache-locality optimizations as well as auto-parallelism and vectorization using a polyhedral model.
[src:terra-language/llvm] llvm-libc is an incomplete, upcoming, ABI independent C standard library designed by and for the LLVM project.
[src:terra-language/llvm] Due to its permissive license, many vendors release their own tuned forks of LLVM.
[src:terra-language/llvm] This is officially recognized by LLVM's documentation, which suggests against using version numbers in feature checks for this reason.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua originated in 1993 as a language for extending software applications to meet the increasing demand for customization at the time.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] It provided the basic facilities of most procedural programming languages, but more complicated or domain-specific features were not included; rather, it included mechanisms for extending the language, allowing programmers to implement such features.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] As Lua was intended to be a general embeddable extension language, the designers of Lua focused on improving its speed, portability, extensibility and ease-of-use in development.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua was created in 1993 by Roberto Ierusalimschy, Luiz Henrique de Figueiredo, and Waldemar Celes, members of the Computer Graphics Technology Group (Tecgraf) at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, in Brazil.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] From 1977 until 1992, Brazil had a policy of strong trade barriers (called a market reserve) for computer hardware and software, believing that Brazil could and should produce its own hardware and software.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In that climate, Tecgraf's clients could not afford, either politically or financially, to buy customized software from abroad; under the market reserve, clients would have to go through a complex bureaucratic process to prove their needs couldn't be met by Brazilian companies.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Those reasons led Tecgraf to implement the basic tools it needed from scratch.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua's predecessors were the data-description and configuration languages Simple Object Language (SOL) and Data-Entry Language (DEL).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] They had been independently developed at Tecgraf in 1992–1993 to add some flexibility into two different projects (both were interactive graphical programs for engineering applications at Petrobras company).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] There was a lack of any flow-control structures in SOL and DEL, and Petrobras felt a growing need to add full programming power to them.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua 1.0 was designed in such a way that its object constructors, being then slightly different from the current light and flexible style, incorporated the data-description syntax of SOL (hence the name Lua: *Sol* meaning "Sun" in Portuguese, and *Lua* meaning "Moon").
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Dobb's Journal*, Lua's creators also state that LISP and Scheme with their single, ubiquitous data-structure mechanism (the list) were a major influence on their decision to develop the table as the primary data structure of Lua.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua semantics have been increasingly influenced by Scheme over time, especially with the introduction of anonymous functions and full lexical scoping.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Several features were added in new Lua versions.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Versions of Lua prior to version 5.0 were released under a license similar to the BSD license.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] From version 5.0 onwards, Lua has been licensed under the MIT License.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Both are permissive free software licences and are almost identical.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua is commonly described as a "multi-paradigm" language, providing a small set of general features that can be extended to fit different problem types.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua does not contain explicit support for inheritance, but allows it to be implemented with metatables.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In general, Lua strives to provide simple, flexible meta-features that can be extended as needed, rather than supply a feature-set specific to one programming paradigm.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] As a result, the base language is light; the full reference interpreter is only about 293 kB compiled and easily adaptable to a broad range of applications.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] As a dynamically typed language intended for use as an extension language or scripting language, Lua is compact enough to fit on a variety of host platforms.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] It supports only a small number of atomic data structures such as Boolean values, numbers (double-precision floating point and 64-bit integers by default) and strings.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Typical data structures such as arrays, sets, lists and records can be represented using Lua's single native data structure, the table, which is essentially a heterogeneous associative array.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua implements a small set of advanced features such as first-class functions, garbage collection, closures, proper tail calls, coercion (automatic conversion between string and number values at run time), coroutines (cooperative multitasking) and dynamic module loading.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The declaration of a variable, without a value.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A comment in Lua starts with a double-hyphen and runs to the end of the line, similar to Ada, Eiffel, Haskell, SQL and VHDL.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Multi-line strings and comments are marked with double square brackets.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua has one type of conditional test: `if then end` with optional `else` and `elseif then` execution control constructs.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua has four types of conditional loops: the `while` loop, the `repeat` loop (similar to a `do while` loop), the numeric `for` loop and the generic `for` loop.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Loops can also be nested (put inside of another loop).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Any future calls to `print` will now be routed through the new function, and because of Lua's lexical scoping, the old print function will only be accessible by the new, modified print.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A new closure for the variable `x` is created every time `addto` is called, so that each new anonymous function returned will always access its own `x` parameter.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The closure is managed by Lua's garbage collector, just like any other object.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Tables are the most important data structures (and, by design, the only built-in composite data type) in Lua and are the foundation of all user-created types.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] They are associative arrays with addition of automatic numeric key and special syntax.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A table is a set of key and data pairs, where the data is referenced by key; in other words, it is a hashed heterogeneous associative array.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Tables are created using the `{}` constructor syntax.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Tables are always passed by reference (see Call by sharing).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A key (index) can be any value except `nil` and NaN, including functions.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A table is often used as structure (or record) by using strings as keys.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Because such use is very common, Lua features a special syntax for accessing such fields.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] By using a table to store related functions, it can act as a namespace.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Tables are automatically assigned a numerical key, enabling them to be used as an array data type.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The first automatic index is 1 rather than 0 as it is for many other programming languages (though an explicit index of 0 is allowed).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A numeric key `1` is distinct from a string key `"1"`.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The length of a table `t` is defined to be any integer index `n` such that `t[n]` is not `nil` and `t[n+1]` is `nil`; moreover, if `t[1]` is `nil`, `n` can be zero.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] For a regular array, with non-nil values from 1 to a given `n`, its length is exactly that `n`, the index of its last value.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] If the array has "holes" (that is, nil values between other non-nil values), then `#t` can be any of the indices that directly precedes a `nil` value (that is, it may consider any such nil value as the end of the array).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Using a hash map to emulate an array is normally slower than using an actual array; however, Lua tables are optimized for use as arrays to help avoid this issue.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Extensible semantics is a key feature of Lua, and the metatable allows powerful customization of tables.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The following example demonstrates an "infinite" table.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] For any `n`, `fibs[n]` will give the `n`-th Fibonacci number using dynamic programming and memoization.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Although Lua does not have a built-in concept of classes, object-oriented programming can be emulated using functions and tables.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] An object is formed by putting methods and fields in a table.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Inheritance (both single and multiple) can be implemented with metatables, delegating nonexistent methods and fields to a parent object.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] There is no such concept as "class" with these techniques; rather, prototypes are used, similar to Self or JavaScript.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] New objects are created either with a factory method (that constructs new objects from scratch) or by cloning an existing object.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Here, `setmetatable` tells Lua to look for an element in the `Vector` table if it is not present in the `vec` table.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] `vec.magnitude`, which is equivalent to `vec["magnitude"]`, first looks in the `vec` table for the `magnitude` element.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The `vec` table does not have a `magnitude` element, but its metatable delegates to the `Vector` table for the `magnitude` element when it's not found in the `vec` table.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua provides some syntactic sugar to facilitate object orientation.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] To declare member functions inside a prototype table, one can use `function table:func(args)`, which is equivalent to `function table.func(self, args)`.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Calling class methods also makes use of the colon: `object:func(args)` is equivalent to `object.func(object, args)`.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] It is possible to use metatables to mimic the behavior of class inheritance in Lua.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In this example, we allow vectors to have their values multiplied by a constant in a derived class.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] It is also possible to implement multiple inheritance; `__index` can either be a function or a table.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Operator overloading can also be done; Lua metatables can have elements such as `__add`, `__sub` and so on.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua programs are not interpreted directly from the textual Lua file, but are compiled into bytecode, which is then run on the Lua virtual machine (VM).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The compiling process is typically invisible to the user and is performed during run-time, especially when a just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler is used, but it can be done offline to increase loading performance or reduce the memory footprint of the host environment by leaving out the compiler.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua bytecode can also be produced and executed from within Lua, using the `dump` function from the string library and the `load/loadstring/loadfile` functions.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua version 5.5.0 is implemented in approximately 32,000 lines of C code.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Like most CPUs, and unlike most virtual machines (which are stack-based), the Lua VM is register-based, and therefore more closely resembles most hardware design.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The register architecture both avoids excessive copying of values, and reduces the total number of instructions per function.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The virtual machine of Lua 5 is one of the first register-based pure VMs to have a wide use.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Parrot and Android's Dalvik are two other well-known register-based VMs.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua is intended to be embedded into other applications, and provides a C API for this purpose.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The API is divided into two parts: the Lua core and the Lua auxiliary library.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The Lua API's design eliminates the need for manual reference counting (management) in C code, unlike Python's API.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The API, like the language, is minimalist.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Advanced functions are provided by the auxiliary library, which consists largely of preprocessor macros which assist with complex table operations.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua provides functions to push and pop most simple C data types (integers, floats, etc.) to and from the stack, and functions to manipulate tables through the stack.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The Lua stack is somewhat different from a traditional stack; the stack can be indexed directly, for example.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Negative indices indicate offsets from the top of the stack.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] For example, −1 is the top (most recently pushed value), while positive indices indicate offsets from the bottom (oldest value).
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Marshalling data between C and Lua functions is also done using the stack.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] To call a Lua function, arguments are pushed onto the stack, and then the `lua_call` is used to call the actual function.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] When writing a C function to be directly called from Lua, the arguments are read from the stack.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] The C API also provides some special tables, located at various "pseudo-indices" in the Lua stack.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] At `LUA_GLOBALSINDEX` prior to Lua 5.2 is the globals table, `_G` from within Lua, which is the main namespace.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] There is also a registry located at `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX` where C programs can store Lua values for later retrieval.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Besides standard library (core) modules it is possible to write extensions using the Lua API.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Extension modules are shared objects which can be used to extend the functions of the interpreter by providing native facilities to Lua scripts.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Lua scripts may load extension modules using `require`, just like modules written in Lua itself, or with `package.loadlib`.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] When a C library is loaded via `require('foo')` Lua will look for the function `luaopen_foo` and call it, which acts as any C function callable from Lua and generally returns a table filled with methods.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] A growing set of modules termed *rocks* are available through a package management system named LuaRocks, in the spirit of CPAN, RubyGems and Python eggs.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Prewritten Lua bindings exist for most popular programming languages, including other scripting languages.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] For C++, there are a number of template-based approaches and some automatic binding generators.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In video game development, Lua is widely used as a scripting language, mainly due to its perceived ease of embedding, fast execution, and short learning curve.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Notable games which use Lua include *Roblox*, *Garry's Mod*, *World of Warcraft*, *Payday 2*, *Project Zomboid*, *Phantasy Star Online 2*, *Dota 2*, *Crysis*, and many others.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] Also, Lua is used in non-video game software, such as Adobe Lightroom, Moho, iClone, Aerospike, and some system software in FreeBSD and NetBSD, and used as a template scripting language on MediaWiki using the Scribunto extension.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In 2003, a poll conducted by GameDev.net showed that Lua was the most popular scripting language for game programming.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] On 12 January 2012, Lua was announced as a winner of the Front Line Award 2011 from the magazine *Game Developer* in the category Programming Tools.
[src:terra-language/lua-programming-language] In addition, the Lua users community provides some *power patches* on top of the reference C implementation.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:terra-language/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:terra-language/multi-stage-programming] In MSP languages, expressions are qualified by notation that specifies the phase at which they are to be evaluated.
[src:terra-language/multi-stage-programming] By allowing the specialization of a program at run-time, MSP can optimize the performance of programs: it can be considered as a form of partial evaluation that performs computations at compile-time as a trade-off to increase the speed of run-time processing.
[src:terra-language/multi-stage-programming] Multi-stage programming languages support constructs similar to the Lisp construct of quotation and `eval`, except that scoping rules are taken into account.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] A **system programming language** is a programming language used for system programming; such languages are designed for writing system software, which usually requires different development approaches when compared with application software.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Edsger Dijkstra referred to these languages as **machine oriented high order languages**, or **mohol**.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] General-purpose programming languages tend to focus on generic features to allow programs written in the language to use the same code on different computing platforms.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Examples of such languages include ALGOL and Pascal.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] This generic quality typically comes at the cost of denying direct access to the machine's internal workings, and this often has negative effects on performance.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] System languages, in contrast, are designed not for compatibility, but for performance and ease of access to the underlying computer hardware while still providing high-level programming concepts like structured programming.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Examples include Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL) and Systems Programming Language (SPL), both of which are ALGOL-like in syntax but tuned to their respective platforms.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Others are cross-platform software, but designed to work close to the hardware, like BLISS, JOVIAL, and BCPL.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Some languages straddle the system and application domains, bridging the gap between these uses.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] The canonical example is C, which is used widely for both system and application programming.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Some modern languages also do this such as Rust and Swift.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] In contrast with application languages, system programming languages typically offer more-direct access to the physical hardware of the machine: an archetypical system programming language in this sense was BCPL.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] System programming languages often lack built-in input/output (I/O) facilities because a system-software project usually develops its own I/O mechanisms or builds on basic monitor I/O or screen management facilities.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] The distinction between languages used for system programming and application programming became blurred over time with the widespread popularity of PL/I, C and Pascal.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] The earliest system software was written in assembly language mostly because no alternative existed, but also for reasons including efficiency of object code, compiling time, and ease of debugging.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Application languages such as FORTRAN were used for system programming, although they usually still required some routines to be written in assembly language.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Other languages in this category include MOL-360 and PL/S.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] As an example, a typical PL360 statement is `R9 := R8 and R7 shll 8 or R6`, signifying that registers 8 and 7 should be and'ed together, the result shifted left 8 bits, the result of that or'ed with the contents of register 6, and the final result placed into register 9.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] While PL360 is at the semantic level of assembly language, another kind of system programming language operates at a higher semantic level, but has specific extensions designed to make the language suitable for system programming.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] An early example of this kind of language is LRLTRAN, which extended Fortran with features for character and bit manipulation, pointers, and directly addressed jump tables.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Subsequently, languages such as C were developed, where the combination of features was sufficient to write system software, and a compiler could be developed that generated efficient object programs on modest hardware.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Such a language generally omits features that cannot be implemented efficiently, and adds a small number of machine-dependent features needed to access specific hardware abilities; inline assembly code, such as C's `asm` statement, is often used for this purpose.
[src:terra-language/system-programming-language] Although many such languages were developed, C and C++ are the ones which survived.
